'\" t
.TH "seat-vtty" "7" "" "seat-vtty"
.\" -----------------------------------------------------------------
.\" -----------------------------------------------------------------
.SH "NAME"
seat-vtty - logind seat
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
.B seat-vtty
is a logind seat, created by the 
.B @udevrulesdir@/72-seat-vtty.rules
file, by assigning the virtual
.B /dev/tty
file to the seat. 

.SH "/dev/tty on seat-vtty"
The device file
.B /dev/tty
is configured to be added to the \fBseat-vtty\fR seat as this device
file exists on all Linux systems, and represents the terminal or
pseudoterminal of the current process (if any), therefore, there are no
effective permissions changes to
.B /dev/tty
for processes running and assigned to the
.B seat-vtty
seat. 
.PP
udev is configured
to set the 
.B master-of-seat
and
.B seat
properties to the
.B /dev/tty
file, so udev adds it to
.B seat-vtty
so that logind actually creates the
.B seat-vtty
seat.

.SH "seat-vtty"
While most seats have various hardware devices like mice, keyboards,
and GPUs assigned to it,
.B seat-vtty
has no hardware assigned to it. The reason for the
.B seat-vtty
seat is for
.BR polkit (8)
access. The vtty backend starts a getty with 
\fBXDG_SEAT\fR=\fIseat\-vtty\fR set so that the session starts on
\fBseat-vtty\fR with complete polkit access, instead of those
of a remote session. This allows commands such as
.BR nmtui (1),
.BR pkexec (1),
.BR udisksctl (1),
and the like to work with complete permissions.
Furthermore 
.BR polkit (8)
is configued so that
.BR vtty-launch (1)
only works on \fBseat-vtty\fR.
.SH "See Also"
.BR vtty (7),
.BR vtty-launch (1)
